<rs id="t18390204-780-punishment-221" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18390204-780-punishment-221" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18390204-780-punishment-221" type="punishmentSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-780-18390204 t18390204-780-punishment-221"></join>Confined Three Months</rs>., <hi rend="smallCaps">THEODORE TILLETT</hi>. I am a widow. The prisoner Tillett it my son—I missed a cloth cloak from a box in my room, in Mark-street, Finsbury, a month ago next Friday—my son came that night, and I gave him into cus<lb></lb>tody</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1324" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1324" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1324" type="surname" value="PEAK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1324" type="given" value="MATTHEW"></interp>MATTHEW PEAK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. I took Tillett into custody, and in consequence of what he told me I went with Brannan to No. 6, Old Cock-lane, Shoreditch, and found Ebbs—I said, "Do you know any thing about the cloak?"—he said, "No, I know nothing about it"—I went to<lb></lb>wards a closet by the fire-place, and Brannan went towards at chest of drawers—Ebbs followed him, and said ht had got the cloak—I then, saw the cloak in Brannan's hands.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he not say, "Oh, yes, there is a cloak," before Brannan found it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot say, because I was look<lb></lb>ing into the cupboard—Brannan was going towards the drawer before he said any thing about having it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1325" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1325" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1325" type="surname" value="BRANNAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1325" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES BRANNAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. On Saturday, the 19th of Janu<lb></lb>ary, I went with Peak to Ebbs's lodging—Peak asked him about the cloak—he said, "I know nothing of a cloak; I have no cloak here"—I west towards a chest of drawers—the prisoner followed me, and opened the drawers—I put my hand upon the cloak, and he did <hi rend="italic">so</hi> at the same time, and said, "Oh, ah, here is a cloak"—I said, "How did you get it?"—he said he lent a boy 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on it, to get his things out of pawn.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you understand whether that boy was Tillett? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not—I have since heard that it was not—I have been looking for one Lenton, but cannot find him—I believe Ebbs is a willow-weaver—I</p>
               <p>found no other stolen property on his premises.</p>
